3. Explain the relationships in business terms

This is where junior developers usually improve the most.

Don't think:

TaskManager imports Task.

Think:

Relationship 1

TaskManager manages Tasks.

Business language:

A manager is responsible for the entire lifecycle of a task.

It creates them.

Updates them.

Deletes them.

Completes them.

Searches them.

Relationship 2

Task has one Status.

Business meaning:

Every task must always have a current state.

Example

TODO

↓

IN_PROGRESS

↓

REVIEW

↓

DONE

A task can never be "between" two statuses.

Relationship 3

Task has one Priority.

Business meaning:

Every task has a level of importance.

Relationship 4

TaskManager uses TaskStorage

Business meaning:

The manager knows how to manage work.

The storage knows how to save work.

These responsibilities are intentionally separate.

4. Domain-specific terminology and patterns

There are several software engineering patterns hiding in this small project.

Domain Model

This is:

class Task

It represents a real business thing.

Not a screen.

Not a file.

An actual concept.

Enum
TaskStatus

TaskPriority

Enums prevent invalid values.

Instead of

"doing"

"started"

"almost"

"yes"

the application forces users into valid business states.

Service Layer

This is

TaskManager

It coordinates business rules.

It doesn't save files.

It doesn't print menus.

It makes business decisions.

Persistence Layer
TaskStorage

Responsible for reading and writing data.

Nothing else.

Entity

The Task class is an entity.

Why?

Because every task has its own identity.

uuid

Every task is unique even if two tasks have the same title.

