Your confusion: TaskStatus(status_filter)

This is the part I'd spend extra time on because it's a common stumbling block.

Suppose the user types

list --status done

Inside the CLI,

args.status

contains

"done"

Now app.py receives

status_filter = "done"

This line executes

status = TaskStatus(status_filter)

Think of it as asking Python:

"Find me the TaskStatus member whose value is 'done'."

Python answers

TaskStatus.DONE

Now the storage layer can compare enums:

task.status == TaskStatus.DONE

instead of comparing raw strings everywhere.

This is safer because enums reduce typos and make the code more expressive.

One small refinement to your understanding

Instead of saying:

"TaskStatus converts raw numbers."

I would write:

"TaskStatus(status_filter) converts a user-provided status string (such as 'done' or 'todo') into a TaskStatus enum object so the rest of the application can work with a controlled set of valid task states."

That's exactly how a senior developer would describe it.


Then, please ask me 3-5 questions that would test my understanding of this domain model. These should be questions that make me think about the business logic, not just the code syntax.

****AIs Response****

1. Why does every Task begin with the status TODO instead of allowing the user to choose any status when creating it?

What this tests: Whether you understand that the application models a task lifecycle. In many businesses, a task is always created as "to do" and only later progresses to "in progress", "review", and "done".

2. Why does the application use TaskStatus and TaskPriority as Enums instead of storing plain strings or integers everywhere?

What this tests: Whether you understand the business value of restricting tasks to valid states and priorities. Enums prevent invalid values like "finished" or "very urgent" from entering the system.

3. A task has both created_at and completed_at. Why are both important from a business perspective?

What this tests: Whether you recognize that the application isn't just storing tasks—it is tracking their history. These timestamps allow features like:

reporting
productivity statistics
completion metrics
overdue calculations
4. If a task is marked as DONE, why does the application also call mark_as_done() instead of only changing the status?

What this tests: Whether you notice that completing a task has business side effects. Besides changing the status, the system records the completion time and updates the last modified time. A business event often affects multiple pieces of data.

5. Suppose the business introduces a new requirement: Archived tasks should no longer appear in normal task lists but should still be stored for historical purposes.

Without thinking about code, what parts of the domain model would you expect to change?

What this tests: Whether you can think like a software designer rather than just a programmer. A good answer might mention:

the task lifecycle (a new status or concept)
filtering logic
listing behavior
statistics
storage

rather than immediately thinking about specific functions.

Bonus question (the one I'd ask a junior during onboarding)

Imagine I delete storage.py tomorrow and replace it with a database implementation.

Which parts of the business logic should remain exactly the same, and why?

If you can answer that confidently, it shows you've understood the separation between:

Domain model (Task, TaskStatus, TaskPriority)
Business logic (TaskManager)
Persistence (TaskStorage)

That separation is one of the most important design ideas in this project.

